> **APJ ABDUL KALAM TECHNOLOGICAL UNIVERSITY (KTU) | 2024 SCHEME**
> - **Course:** PCEOL408 - OBJECT ORIENTED PROGRAMMING (JAVA) LAB
> - **Module:** Module Experiment 2
> - **Topic:** Write a Java program with an Employee class having Name, Phone number, Address, and Salary as members and a printSalary() method, with Officer and Manager classes inheriting from Employee and having 'specialization' and 'department' as data members respectively

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

**Inheritance** in Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) is a fundamental mechanism by which a new class (called the **subclass**, **derived class**, or **child class**) is created from an existing class (called the **superclass**, **base class**, or **parent class**), thereby acquiring — and potentially extending or modifying — its attributes (data members) and behaviors (member methods).

In the context of the KTU 2024 Scheme **PCEOL408 – Object Oriented Programming (Java) Lab**, Experiment 2 specifically evaluates a student's ability to implement **single-level inheritance** using Java's `extends` keyword, demonstrating:

- A **generalized parent class** (`Employee`) encapsulating common attributes (`name`, `phoneNumber`, `address`, `salary`) and a common behavior (`printSalary()`).
- **Two specialized child classes** (`Officer` and `Manager`) that inherit from the parent and add their **own unique attributes** (`specialization` and `department` respectively).

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Syllabus Highlight (Module 2 – Inheritance):** Students must be able to *design and implement class hierarchies using single inheritance, demonstrate method inheritance, override or extend superclass methods, and instantiate subclass objects that leverage inherited members without redundancy.*

---

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Think of a **corporate organization chart**:

- Every person in the company is an **Employee**. They all share universal traits: a *name*, a *phone number*, an *office address*, and a *monthly salary*. This is your **Employee** superclass — the universal template.
- However, not every employee is the same. An **Officer** is a specialized type of employee with a *specialization* (e.g., "HR Operations" or "Cyber Security"). A **Manager** is another specialized type with a *department* (e.g., "Finance" or "R&D").

Instead of re-writing the common fields (name, phone, address, salary) **three separate times** for three different job roles, inheritance lets the **Officer** and **Manager** classes **automatically inherit** all common fields from `Employee` and just *add* what makes them unique. This is the OOP principle of **code reusability** in action.

| Real-World Entity | Java Construct |
|---|---|
| Universal concept of "Employee" | `class Employee` (Superclass) |
| Specific role of "Officer" | `class Officer extends Employee` (Subclass) |
| Specific role of "Manager" | `class Manager extends Employee` (Subclass) |
| Common traits of all employees | Data members inherited from `Employee` |
| Unique traits of a role | Additional data members in the subclass |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why inheritance matters in KTU labs:** The KTU 2024 scheme emphasizes **DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)** principles. Writing `name`, `phone`, `address`, `salary` separately in three classes would violate DRY and would be marked down in the lab record and viva.

---

## 1.3 Key Terminology Used in This Experiment

| Term | Definition | KTU-Standard Notation |
|---|---|---|
| **Superclass** | The class whose features are inherited | `Employee` |
| **Subclass** | The class that inherits features | `Officer`, `Manager` |
| **`extends` keyword** | Java keyword used to establish inheritance | `class Officer extends Employee` |
| **Data Member** | A variable declared inside a class | `String name;` |
| **Member Method** | A function declared inside a class | `void printSalary()` |
| **Single Inheritance** | One subclass inheriting from one superclass | This experiment |
| **Code Reusability** | Reusing existing code via inheritance | KTU 2024 CO assessment focus |
| **Hierarchical Inheritance** | Multiple subclasses inheriting from a single superclass | **Used in this experiment** |

> [!TIP]
> This experiment is a textbook case of **Hierarchical Inheritance** — multiple child classes (`Officer`, `Manager`) inheriting from a **single** parent class (`Employee`). This is one of the four types of inheritance recognized in the KTU 2024 syllabus and is a **frequently asked viva question**.

---

## 1.4 Physical / Standard Metrics (Java-Specific Constants)

In this experiment, the relevant "constants" are Java language specifications:

- **Java Access Modifier Defaults** — The KTU board examiner expects the use of `private` for data encapsulation with `public` getter/setter methods, demonstrating **data hiding**.
- **Standard Java Naming Conventions**:
  - Class names use **PascalCase** → `Employee`, `Officer`, `Manager`
  - Method names use **camelCase** → `printSalary()`, `getName()`
  - Variable names use **camelCase** → `phoneNumber`, `specialization`
- **Java Method Signature Rule** — A method's signature is `(methodName, parameterTypes)`. The return type is **NOT** part of the signature.
<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Concept Sheet

## 2.1 Theoretical Foundations of Inheritance

The following **logical pillars** underpin inheritance in Java and form the theoretical basis for the experiment's expected output.

### Pillar 1: The `extends` Keyword and Class Hierarchy

When a class is declared with `extends`, Java internally:

1. **Allocates memory** for all inherited data members in the subclass object.
2. **Reserves method slots** for inherited methods, accessible as if they were defined locally.
3. **Establishes an "IS-A" relationship**: An `Officer` **IS-A** `Employee`; a `Manager` **IS-A** `Employee`. This is the *Liskov Substitution Principle* in its most basic form.

> [!NOTE]
> In Java, **every class implicitly extends `Object`** if no `extends` clause is specified. Thus `Employee` → `Object` is an implicit chain.

### Pillar 2: Constructor Chaining via `super()`

When a subclass object is created, Java's two-phase initialization kicks in:

- **Phase 1:** The superclass constructor executes **first** (called via implicit or explicit `super()`).
- **Phase 2:** The subclass constructor body executes **afterwards**.

If the superclass has a **parameterized constructor** and no default constructor, the subclass **must** explicitly call `super(args)` as the first statement.

### Pillar 3: Method Inheritance and `printSalary()`

The method `printSalary()` is defined **once** in the `Employee` class. Both `Officer` and `Manager` objects can call it without redeclaration. This is the *single most important* concept KTU examiners test in viva.

### Pillar 4: Data Member Inheritance (Private vs. Protected vs. Public)

| Modifier | Accessible in Subclass? | KTU Recommendation |
|---|---|---|
| `private` | ❌ No (use getters/setters) | **Best Practice** — Encapsulation |
| `protected` | ✅ Yes | Use only when subclass needs direct access |
| `public` | ✅ Yes | Avoid for data members (breaks encapsulation) |
| *default (package-private)* | ✅ Yes (same package) | Rarely used in KTU labs |

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Viva Trap:** A student may claim "private members are inherited." This is **FALSE**. Private members **are allocated** in the subclass object (memory-wise), but they are **not directly accessible** by name in the subclass. They can only be accessed via public/protected getter methods.

---

## 2.2 KTU High-Yield "Formula Sheet" — Inheritance in Java

| Concept | Syntax / Rule | Example | KTU Exam Weight |
|---|---|---|---|
| Single Inheritance | `class Child extends Parent` | `class Officer extends Employee` | **High** |
| Hierarchical Inheritance | Multiple children from one parent | `Officer`, `Manager` from `Employee` | **High** |
| Multilevel Inheritance | `class A` → `class B` → `class C` | Not used in this experiment | Medium |
| Multiple Inheritance | `class C extends A, B` | **NOT ALLOWED in Java** (use interfaces) | **High (Theory)** |
| `super` keyword | Refers to immediate parent | `super(name, phone, address, salary)` | **High** |
| Method Overriding | Same signature in subclass | `printSalary()` redefined | Medium |
| `instanceof` Operator | Checks object type | `obj instanceof Officer` | Medium |
| Constructor Chaining | Implicit/explicit `super()` call | First line of subclass constructor | **High** |
| `Object` class | Root of all Java classes | Implicit super of `Employee` | Low |
| `final` class | Cannot be inherited | `final class Employee` | Low |

---

## 2.3 Why Inheritance? Real-World Engineering Utility

In **enterprise software engineering**, inheritance is the backbone of frameworks like:

- **Java Swing / JavaFX:** `JButton extends AbstractButton extends JComponent extends Container extends Component`
- **Spring Framework:** All custom controllers extend base controller classes
- **Android Development:** `AppCompatActivity extends Activity` — every Android screen inherits lifecycle methods

In **KTU 2024 CO mapping**, this experiment primarily targets:

- **CO2:** *Implement Object-Oriented programming concepts using Java* (Bloom Level: Apply)
- **CO3:** *Design and develop Java programs using inheritance and polymorphism* (Bloom Level: Create)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Engineering Utility:** In real-world HR Management Systems (e.g., SAP, Workday), the `Employee` → `Officer/Manager` hierarchy is a literal, production-grade design pattern. Mastering this experiment prepares you for industry-grade Object Modeling (UML class diagrams).
<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# 3. Step-by-Step Implementation, Code Analysis & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Algorithm / Program Design Steps (For KTU Lab Record)

The following **algorithmic blueprint** is the standard KTU-recommended procedure for writing this program. Each step must appear in your lab record's "Algorithm" section.

### Step-by-Step Program Construction Logic

| Step | Action | Rationale |
|---|---|---|
| **1** | Define `Employee` class with private data members: `name`, `phoneNumber`, `address`, `salary`. | Encapsulation — data hiding is a KTU marking criterion. |
| **2** | Create a **parameterized constructor** for `Employee` to initialize all four fields. | Enables object creation with values; supports `super()` chaining. |
| **3** | Define `printSalary()` method inside `Employee` that prints the salary. | Common behavior to be inherited by all subclasses. |
| **4** | Define `Officer` class using `extends Employee`, adding `specialization` data member. | Establishes IS-A relationship. |
| **5** | Define `Officer` constructor that calls `super(...)` to initialize parent fields, then sets `specialization`. | Mandatory — parent fields must be initialized via superclass constructor. |
| **6** | Define `Manager` class using `extends Employee`, adding `department` data member. | Second branch of hierarchical inheritance. |
| **7** | Define `Manager` constructor that calls `super(...)`, then sets `department`. | Same rationale as Step 5. |
| **8** | In the `main` method, create one `Officer` object and one `Manager` object with sample data. | Demonstrates instantiation and method invocation. |
| **9** | Call `printSalary()` on both objects. Observe that the same inherited method works for both. | Proves inheritance of behavior. |
| **10** | Print the unique attributes (`specialization` / `department`) separately. | Proves the subclasses have their own additional data. |

---

## 3.2 Complete Java Source Code (KTU Board-Standard Version)

The following is the **canonical, KTU-examiner-expected** implementation. Use this as your lab record reference.

```java
// File: Employee.java
// Superclass definition
class Employee {
    // Step 1: Private data members (Encapsulation)
    private String name;
    private String phoneNumber;
    private String address;
    private double salary;

    // Step 2: Parameterized constructor
    public Employee(String name, String phoneNumber, String address, double salary) {
        this.name = name;
        this.phoneNumber = phoneNumber;
        this.address = address;
        this.salary = salary;
    }

    // Step 3: Common method to print salary
    public void printSalary() {
        System.out.println("Salary of " + name + " is: Rs. " + salary);
    }

    // Optional but recommended: Getters for accessing private fields
    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }

    public String getPhoneNumber() {
        return phoneNumber;
    }

    public String getAddress() {
        return address;
    }

    public double getSalary() {
        return salary;
    }
}
```

```java
// File: Officer.java
// Subclass 1 - Officer
class Officer extends Employee {
    // Step 4: Unique data member
    private String specialization;

    // Step 5: Constructor with super() call
    public Officer(String name, String phoneNumber, String address,
                   double salary, String specialization) {
        // Must be the FIRST statement
        super(name, phoneNumber, address, salary);
        this.specialization = specialization;
    }

    public String getSpecialization() {
        return specialization;
    }

    public void printSpecialization() {
        System.out.println("Officer Specialization: " + specialization);
    }
}
```

```java
// File: Manager.java
// Subclass 2 - Manager
class Manager extends Employee {
    // Step 6: Unique data member
    private String department;

    // Step 7: Constructor with super() call
    public Manager(String name, String phoneNumber, String address,
                   double salary, String department) {
        // Must be the FIRST statement
        super(name, phoneNumber, address, salary);
        this.department = department;
    }

    public String getDepartment() {
        return department;
    }

    public void printDepartment() {
        System.out.println("Manager Department: " + department);
    }
}
```

```java
// File: EmployeeHierarchyDemo.java
// Main driver class
public class EmployeeHierarchyDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Step 8: Create Officer object
        Officer officer = new Officer("Ananya Krishnan",
                                      "+91-9847012345",
                                      "Trivandrum, Kerala",
                                      75000.00,
                                      "Cyber Security");

        // Step 8: Create Manager object
        Manager manager = new Manager("Rajeev Menon",
                                      "+91-9446789012",
                                      "Kochi, Kerala",
                                      120000.00,
                                      "Finance & Accounts");

        // Step 9: Call inherited printSalary() on both
        officer.printSalary();
        manager.printSalary();

        // Step 10: Print unique attributes
        System.out.println("--- Officer Details ---");
        System.out.println("Name          : " + officer.getName());
        System.out.println("Phone         : " + officer.getPhoneNumber());
        System.out.println("Address       : " + officer.getAddress());
        System.out.println("Specialization: " + officer.getSpecialization());

        System.out.println("\n--- Manager Details ---");
        System.out.println("Name      : " + manager.getName());
        System.out.println("Phone     : " + manager.getPhoneNumber());
        System.out.println("Address   : " + manager.getAddress());
        System.out.println("Department: " + manager.getDepartment());
    }
}
```

---

## 3.3 Expected Output (For Lab Record Verification)

```
Salary of Ananya Krishnan is: Rs. 75000.0
Salary of Rajeev Menon is: Rs. 120000.0
--- Officer Details ---
Name          : Ananya Krishnan
Phone         : +91-9847012345
Address       : Trivandrum, Kerala
Specialization: Cyber Security

--- Manager Details ---
Name      : Rajeev Menon
Phone     : +91-9446789012
Address   : Kochi, Kerala
Department: Finance & Accounts
```

---

## 3.4 Analytical Matrix — Concept-to-Output Mapping

| Concept Demonstrated | Code Line(s) | Output Evidence |
|---|---|---|
| **Encapsulation** | `private String name;` | Field not directly accessible from `main` |
| **Parameterized Constructor** | `public Employee(String name, ...)` | Called via `super()` in subclasses |
| **Single Inheritance** | `class Officer extends Employee` | Officer object has Employee properties |
| **Hierarchical Inheritance** | Both `Officer` and `Manager` extend `Employee` | Two sibling subclasses share one parent |
| **Constructor Chaining** | `super(name, phoneNumber, address, salary);` | Parent fields initialized before child constructor body |
| **Method Inheritance** | `officer.printSalary();` | Inherited method called without redeclaration |
| **Subclass-Specific Behavior** | `officer.printSpecialization();` | Method exists only in `Officer` |
| **Data Member Specificity** | `String specialization;` | Exists only in `Officer`, not in `Manager` |

---

## 3.5 Step-by-Step Dry Run (Memory & Execution Trace)

This is what KTU examiners expect in the viva when they ask: *"Walk me through the execution."*

| Execution Phase | What Happens in Memory | Stack Frame |
|---|---|---|
| `main()` invoked | JVM pushes `main` frame onto call stack | `main` |
| `Officer officer = new Officer(...)` | Heap allocates memory for: `{name, phoneNumber, address, salary, specialization}` (5 fields) | `Officer.<init>` |
| Constructor enters `super(...)` | JVM pushes `Employee` constructor frame | `Employee.<init>` |
| `Employee` constructor initializes 4 fields | Heap fields populated: `name="Ananya"`, etc. | `Employee.<init>` |
| `Employee` constructor returns | Frame popped; control returns to `Officer` constructor | `Officer.<init>` |
| `this.specialization = ...` | 5th field populated in heap | `Officer.<init>` |
| `Officer` constructor returns | Frame popped; reference `officer` points to heap object | `main` |
| Same for `Manager` | New heap allocation with 5 fields (its own `department`) | — |
| `officer.printSalary()` | `printSalary` frame pushed, accesses `salary` field, prints, pops | `printSalary` |
| `manager.printSalary()` | Same inherited method, different object's data | `printSalary` |

> [!TIP]
> **Viva Tip:** When asked "How many fields does an `Officer` object have?" — the answer is **5** (4 inherited + 1 own). The fact that 4 are private and inaccessible by name does not change their existence in memory.
<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

<!-- SECTION_4_START -->
# 4. Structural Diagrams & Schematics

## 4.1 Class Hierarchy Diagram (Mermaid UML)

The following Mermaid block renders the **UML class diagram** of the inheritance hierarchy. This is **diagram type 1 — Class Structure**.

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class Employee {
        -String name
        -String phoneNumber
        -String address
        -double salary
        +Employee(String, String, String, double)
        +printSalary() void
        +getName() String
        +getPhoneNumber() String
        +getAddress() String
        +getSalary() double
    }

    class Officer {
        -String specialization
        +Officer(String, String, String, double, String)
        +getSpecialization() String
        +printSpecialization() void
    }

    class Manager {
        -String department
        +Manager(String, String, String, double, String)
        +getDepartment() String
        +printDepartment() void
    }

    Employee <|-- Officer : extends
    Employee <|-- Manager : extends
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Reading the diagram:** Solid lines with **hollow triangular arrowheads** point from subclass to superclass. The `-` prefix denotes `private` visibility; `+` denotes `public`. This is the standard UML notation taught in KTU's Software Engineering module.

---

