    start([Program Start]) --> mainEntry[main method invoked]
    mainEntry --> createOfficer[Create Officer object with 5 args]
    createOfficer --> superCall1[Call super constructor of Employee]
    superCall1 --> initParent1[Initialize name, phone, address, salary]
    initParent1 --> initSpec[Initialize specialization]
    initSpec --> createManager[Create Manager object with 5 args]
    createManager --> superCall2[Call super constructor of Employee]
    superCall2 --> initParent2[Initialize name, phone, address, salary]
    initParent2 --> initDept[Initialize department]
    initDept --> printOfficerSalary[Call officer.printSalary inherited]
    printOfficerSalary --> printManagerSalary[Call manager.printSalary inherited]
    printManagerSalary --> printOfficerDetails[Print Officer unique details]
    printOfficerDetails --> printManagerDetails[Print Manager unique details]
    printManagerDetails --> endProg([Program End])
```

---

## 4.4 Inheritance Type Comparison Diagram

For viva reference, the following diagram situates this experiment within the **inheritance taxonomy**.

```mermaid
graph LR
    inheritanceTypes["Java Inheritance Types"]
    inheritanceTypes --> single["Single Inheritance"]
    inheritanceTypes --> multilevel["Multilevel Inheritance"]
    inheritanceTypes --> hierarchical["Hierarchical Inheritance"]
    inheritanceTypes --> multiple["Multiple Inheritance NOT allowed via class"]
    inheritanceTypes --> hybrid["Hybrid Inheritance via interfaces"]

    hierarchical --> empExp["THIS EXPERIMENT: Employee → Officer, Manager"]
    single --> singleEx["Example: Animal → Dog"]
    multilevel --> multiEx["Example: A → B → C"]
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Viva Question Bank Hit:** *"What type of inheritance does this program demonstrate?"* — The correct answer is **Hierarchical Inheritance** (one parent, multiple children). Some students mistakenly say "multiple inheritance" — this is **wrong** because each child has only one parent.
<!-- SECTION_4_END -->

<!-- SECTION_5_START -->
# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

### **Question A1** `[KTU University Exam - May 2024]`

**Q: What is inheritance in Java? Name the keyword used to implement inheritance and state the type of inheritance demonstrated in the Employee–Officer–Manager program.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

Inheritance is an OOP mechanism that allows a new class (subclass) to acquire the properties and methods of an existing class (superclass), promoting **code reusability** and establishing an **IS-A relationship**. The keyword used is **`extends`**.

In the given program, `Officer` and `Manager` both inherit from a single superclass `Employee`. Since multiple subclasses inherit from a single parent, this is an example of **Hierarchical Inheritance**. *(1 mark for definition, 1 mark for keyword, 1 mark for inheritance type identification.)*

---

### **Question A2** `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]`

**Q: Differentiate between `super` and `this` keywords in Java with respect to the Employee hierarchy program.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

| Aspect | `this` | `super` |
|---|---|---|
| **Refers to** | Current object of the class | Immediate parent (superclass) object |
| **Usage in Employee program** | `this.name = name;` (resolves local-instance ambiguity) | `super(name, phoneNumber, address, salary);` (calls parent constructor from `Officer`/`Manager`) |
| **Constructor call** | `this()` calls another constructor of the **same** class | `super()` calls the constructor of the **parent** class |
| **Position rule** | Can appear anywhere | `super()` must be the **first** statement in a constructor (if used) |

*(1 mark per major difference point × 3 = 3 marks.)*

---

## 5.2 Part B — Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each, Internal Choice)

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning:**
> - **Loses 2 marks** if `private` data members are used **without** getter methods (breaks encapsulation).
> - **Loses 2 marks** if `super(...)` is **missing or placed incorrectly** (must be the first line).
> - **Loses 1 mark** if no parameterized constructor is defined in the superclass.
> - **Loses 2 marks** if class names don't follow **PascalCase** convention.
> - **Loses 1 mark** if the output is not verified/runs with errors at the time of lab evaluation.

---

### **Question B-A (14 Marks)** `[KTU University Exam - May 2024]`

**Q: Write a Java program to create a class `Employee` with data members `Name`, `Phone number`, `Address`, and `Salary`, and a method `printSalary()`. Derive two classes `Officer` (with additional data member `specialization`) and `Manager` (with additional data member `department`) from `Employee`. Display the details of one Officer and one Manager. (14 marks)**

#### **Sub-part (a) — Class Design and Implementation [7 marks]**

**Solution Outline (Model Answer):**

**Step 1: Superclass `Employee`** [3 marks]
- Four `private` data members: `name`, `phoneNumber`, `address`, `salary` (use `private` for encapsulation — *1 mark*).
- Parameterized constructor initializing all four fields using `this` keyword (*1 mark*).
- `public void printSalary()` method that prints the salary in a formatted way (*1 mark*).

**Step 2: Subclass `Officer`** [2 marks]
- Declaration: `class Officer extends Employee` (*0.5 marks*).
- Private field `String specialization` (*0.5 marks*).
- Constructor calling `super(name, phoneNumber, address, salary)` as the first statement, then initializing `specialization` (*1 mark*).

**Step 3: Subclass `Manager`** [2 marks]
- Declaration: `class Manager extends Employee` (*0.5 marks*).
- Private field `String department` (*0.5 marks*).
- Constructor calling `super(...)` then initializing `department` (*1 mark*).

**Full Code for Sub-part (a):**

```java
class Employee {
    private String name;
    private String phoneNumber;
    private String address;
    private double salary;

    public Employee(String name, String phoneNumber,
                    String address, double salary) {
        this.name = name;
        this.phoneNumber = phoneNumber;
        this.address = address;
        this.salary = salary;
    }

    public void printSalary() {
        System.out.println("Employee Name: " + name
                         + " | Salary: Rs. " + salary);
    }

    // Getters (for viva)
    public String getName()        { return name; }
    public String getPhoneNumber() { return phoneNumber; }
    public String getAddress()     { return address; }
    public double getSalary()      { return salary; }
}

class Officer extends Employee {
    private String specialization;

    public Officer(String name, String phoneNumber, String address,
                   double salary, String specialization) {
        super(name, phoneNumber, address, salary);
        this.specialization = specialization;
    }

    public String getSpecialization() { return specialization; }
}

class Manager extends Employee {
    private String department;

    public Manager(String name, String phoneNumber, String address,
                   double salary, String department) {
        super(name, phoneNumber, address, salary);
        this.department = department;
    }

    public String getDepartment() { return department; }
}
```

#### **Sub-part (b) — `main` Method and Output Verification [7 marks]**

**Solution Outline (Model Answer):**

**Step 1: Driver class with `main` method** [2 marks]
- Create an `Officer` object with sample data (*1 mark*).
- Create a `Manager` object with sample data (*1 mark*).

**Step 2: Display logic** [3 marks]
- Call `printSalary()` on the `Officer` object (inherited method) (*1 mark*).
- Call `printSalary()` on the `Manager` object (inherited method) (*1 mark*).
- Print unique attributes (`specialization`, `department`) using getters (*1 mark*).

**Step 3: Output trace and justification** [2 marks]
- State the expected output (*1 mark*).
- Explain why `printSalary()` works for both objects (method inheritance) (*1 mark*).

**Full Code for Sub-part (b):**

```java
public class EmployeeDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Officer officer = new Officer("Ananya", "+91-9847012345",
                                      "Trivandrum", 75000, "Cyber Security");
        Manager manager = new Manager("Rajeev", "+91-9446789012",
                                      "Kochi", 120000, "Finance");

        System.out.println("--- Officer ---");
        officer.printSalary();
        System.out.println("Specialization: " + officer.getSpecialization());

        System.out.println("\n--- Manager ---");
        manager.printSalary();
        System.out.println("Department: " + manager.getDepartment());
    }
}
```

**Expected Output:**

```
--- Officer ---
