## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Exception Handling** in Java is a powerful mechanism that allows a program to handle runtime errors (exceptions) gracefully, ensuring normal flow of the application is maintained. The four foundational keywords are **`try`**, **`catch`**, **`throws`**, and **`finally`**, each forming a distinct part of the **Exception Handling Framework** defined in `java.lang`.

- **`try`**: A block that encloses code which **might** throw an exception. It acts as a "guarded region."
- **`catch`**: A block that **handles** the exception type declared in its parameter. Multiple `catch` blocks may follow a single `try`.
- **`throws`**: A keyword used in a **method signature** to declare that the method may propagate one or more exceptions to the caller.
- **`finally`**: A block that **always executes** after the `try` (or `try-catch`), regardless of whether an exception occurred or was handled. Used for cleanup operations.

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Imagine you are **walking on a tightrope** across a river. You know there is a risk of slipping.

| Java Keyword | Real-World Analogy |
|---|---|
| `try` | The tightrope walk itself — *a risky action* that may succeed or fail. |
| `catch` | The **safety net** that catches you if you fall, and decides what to do next. |
| `throws` | A **warning signboard** at the start of the rope saying "Caution: Risk of falling, do not hold us responsible." |
| `finally` | The **mandatory medical checkup** after the walk — happens whether you fell or not. |

> [!NOTE]
> The KTU 2024 Scheme explicitly tests the ability to *combine* all four keywords in a single coherent program. Memorize this tightrope analogy — it will help in viva voce questions worth **2 marks**.

### 1.3 Exception Hierarchy Snapshot

Every exception in Java is a subclass of `java.lang.Throwable`. The two principal branches are:

- **`Error`** → Severe problems (e.g., `OutOfMemoryError`), **not** meant to be caught.
- **`Exception`** → Recoverable conditions, the focus of program-level handling.
    - **Checked Exceptions** → Detected at **compile-time** (e.g., `IOException`).
    - **Unchecked Exceptions** → Detected at **runtime** (e.g., `ArithmeticException`, `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException`).

