## 3. Step-by-Step Program Construction & Analytical Walkthrough

### 3.1 Complete Java Program (Exam-Ready)

```java
// File: ExceptionDemo.java
// PCEOL408 - Module Experiment 2

import java.util.Scanner;
import java.io.IOException;

// Class A: Demonstrates the 'throws' keyword
class Divider {
    // 'throws ArithmeticException' declares that this method
    // may propagate an unchecked exception to the caller.
    double divide(int numerator, int denominator) throws ArithmeticException {
        if (denominator == 0) {
            // 'throw' explicitly creates and dispatches an exception object
            throw new ArithmeticException("Denominator cannot be zero!");
        }
        return (double) numerator / denominator;
    }
}

// Class B: Demonstrates a checked exception using 'throws'
class FileAccessor {
    // 'throws IOException' forces the caller to handle OR re-declare it
    void readFile(String filename) throws IOException {
        if (filename == null || filename.isEmpty()) {
            throw new IOException("Filename is invalid or empty.");
        }
        System.out.println("Reading file: " + filename);
    }
}

// Main Driver Class
public class ExceptionDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        Divider divider = new Divider();
        FileAccessor fileAccessor = new FileAccessor();

        // -------- Demonstration 1: try - multiple catch - finally --------
        System.out.println("=== Demonstration 1: try / catch / finally ===");
        try {
            System.out.print("Enter numerator   : ");
            int a = sc.nextInt();
            System.out.print("Enter denominator : ");
            int b = sc.nextInt();

            double result = divider.divide(a, b);   // may throw ArithmeticException
            System.out.println("Result = " + result);
        }
        catch (ArithmeticException ae) {
            // Specific exception caught first
            System.out.println("Caught ArithmeticException: " + ae.getMessage());
        }
        catch (Exception e) {
            // Generic catch acts as a safety net
            System.out.println("Caught Generic Exception: " + e.getMessage());
        }
        finally {
            // Always executes — used here for cleanup
            System.out.println("[finally] Block 1 executed — division operation finished.");
        }

        // -------- Demonstration 2: throws with checked exception --------
        System.out.println("\n=== Demonstration 2: throws with checked exception ===");
        try {
            fileAccessor.readFile("");   // empty string triggers IOException
        }
        catch (IOException ioe) {
            System.out.println("Caught IOException: " + ioe.getMessage());
        }
        finally {
            System.out.println("[finally] Block 2 executed — file operation finished.");
        }

        // -------- Demonstration 3: finally executes EVEN on no exception --------
        System.out.println("\n=== Demonstration 3: finally on normal flow ===");
        try {
            System.out.println("Inside try — no exception here.");
        }
        finally {
            System.out.println("[finally] Block 3 executed — no exception occurred.");
        }

        sc.close();
    }
}
```

### 3.2 Step-by-Step Logical Walkthrough

**Step 1 — Compilation Phase**

The compiler verifies the `FileAccessor.readFile()` method. Because it declares `throws IOException` (a **checked** exception), the calling code inside `main()` **must** either catch it via `try-catch` OR re-declare with another `throws`. Our program does the former, so compilation succeeds.

**Step 2 — Runtime Phase, Demonstration 1**

$$
\text{Numerator} = a, \quad \text{Denominator} = b
$$

$$
\text{If } b \neq 0 \implies \text{Result} = \frac{a}{b}, \quad \text{then } \texttt{finally} \text{ runs.}
$$

$$
\text{If } b = 0 \implies \texttt{ArithmeticException thrown} \rightarrow \texttt{first matching catch runs} \rightarrow \texttt{finally runs.}
$$

**Step 3 — Catch Order Verification**

The block

```java
catch (ArithmeticException ae) { ... }
catch (Exception e)        { ... }
```

is valid because `ArithmeticException` is a **subclass** of `Exception`. Reversing the order would cause a **compilation error** ("unreachable catch block"), as `Exception` would already absorb all subclass exceptions.

**Step 4 — Finally Execution Proof**

Demonstration 3 proves that `finally` runs even when the `try` block completes normally — a frequent viva question.

