#### **Question A (14 Marks)** — *Full exception handling with multiple keywords*

**[KTU University Exam – Dec 2024, Model Paper Pattern]**

**(a)** Explain the architecture of Java's exception handling mechanism with a neat block diagram. Discuss the role of `try`, `catch`, `throws`, and `finally`. **(7 marks)**

**Model Solution:**

Java's exception handling mechanism is built upon five keywords: `try`, `catch`, `finally`, `throw`, and `throws`. The architecture is rooted in the class `java.lang.Throwable`, which has two principal subclasses — `Error` and `Exception`.

- **`try` block** encapsulates code that may generate an exception. The JVM monitors this region line-by-line.
- **`catch` block** is the handler. It declares the type of exception it can handle via its parameter (a class reference). Multiple `catch` blocks may follow a single `try`, evaluated in top-to-bottom order, with the **most specific exception type placed first** to avoid "unreachable catch" compile errors.
- **`finally` block** runs unconditionally after the `try` (and optional `catch`). Its principal engineering use is resource cleanup.
- **`throws` keyword** in a method signature declares that the method does not handle the listed exception(s); instead, the responsibility shifts to the calling method.
- **`throw` statement** explicitly dispatches an exception object.

**Block Diagram (Text Representation for Answer Sheet):**

```
[Caller Method]
      |
      | (calls)
      v
[Method Signature: void compute() throws IOException]
      |
      | (invoked from within)
      v
+------------------------------+
|        try { ... }           |  <-- Guarded region
+------------------------------+
      |        |        |
      |  exc?  |  no exc?|
      v        v        v
+---------+  +---------+   +----------+
| catch   |  | skip    |   | (common) |
| (Excptn)|  | catch   |   |  finally | <-- Always runs
+---------+  +---------+   +----------+
```

**Real-world analogy:** Like an industrial safety net — even if the worker (try) succeeds or fails, the safety inspection (finally) is mandatory before the assembly line proceeds. (7 marks)

