#### **Question B (14 Marks)** — *Internal Choice Alternative*

**[KTU University Exam – May 2024, Model Paper Pattern]**

**(a)** Differentiate between **checked** and **unchecked** exceptions in Java with suitable examples. Explain how `throws` is mandatory for one category but not the other. **(7 marks)**

**Model Solution:**

| Feature | Checked Exceptions | Unchecked Exceptions |
|---|---|---|
| Detection | At **compile time** | At **runtime** |
| Parent Class | `Exception` (not `RuntimeException`) | `RuntimeException` (and its subclasses) |
| `throws` Mandatory? | **Yes** — compiler enforces handling/declaration | **No** — compiler does not enforce |
| Typical Examples | `IOException`, `SQLException`, `ClassNotFoundException` | `ArithmeticException`, `NullPointerException`, `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` |
| Engineering Context | External resource interactions (file, network, DB) | Programming logic errors (bad math, null refs) |

**Why `throws` is mandatory for checked:**
The Java compiler performs *checked exception analysis* to ensure robustness for predictable, externally-triggered failures. If a method may throw a checked exception, the compiler forces either a `try-catch` or a `throws` clause in the signature, ensuring the calling layer acknowledges and handles the risk.

**Example:**

```java
// Checked — throws required
void openFile() throws IOException {
    FileReader fr = new FileReader("data.txt");
}

// Unchecked — throws optional
int compute(int x) {
    return 10 / x;   // may throw ArithmeticException silently
}
```

(7 marks)

