## SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

**Thread Synchronization** in Java is the mechanism that ensures that **two or more concurrent threads do not simultaneously execute a shared resource's critical section**, thereby preventing race conditions and data inconsistency. According to the KTU 2024 syllabus (PCEOL408), synchronization is implemented using the `synchronized` keyword, which acquires an **intrinsic lock (monitor)** associated with every Java object.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Definition (Verbatim):** *Thread synchronization is a process of allowing only a single thread to access a shared resource at any given point of time to maintain data consistency and prevent race conditions.*

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — The "Single Bathroom Key" Model

Imagine a **public restroom** in a railway station:

- There is **only one key** for the bathroom door.
- A person **acquires the key** before entering → this is the thread acquiring the **intrinsic lock**.
- While the person is inside, **no one else can enter** → other threads are **blocked** in the waiting state.
- When the person **finishes and returns the key** → the next waiting person **grabs the key** and enters → this is `lock release` and `notify()`.
- If there is **no key** (i.e., no synchronization), multiple people barge in simultaneously, leading to **chaos** → this is the **race condition**.

> [!NOTE]
> **Why is synchronization needed?**
> When multiple threads access a shared mutable resource (e.g., a bank account balance), without synchronization, the interleaving of operations can corrupt the data. This is called a **race condition**, and synchronization eliminates it by enforcing **mutual exclusion**.

### 1.3 Key Terminology Table

| Term | Definition | KTU Significance |
|------|-----------|------------------|
| **Race Condition** | Outcome depends on unpredictable thread scheduling order | Direct KTU viva question |
| **Critical Section** | Code block accessing shared resource | Must be guarded by lock |
| **Monitor / Intrinsic Lock** | Per-object lock managed by JVM | Every Java object has exactly **one** |
| **Mutual Exclusion** | Only one thread executes critical section at a time | Achieved via `synchronized` |
| **Deadlock** | Two threads waiting forever for each other's lock | Avoid via lock ordering |
| **Starvation** | Thread perpetually denied lock access | Mitigated by fair locks |

