## SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 The Three Pillars of Java Synchronization

The KTU 2024 scheme categorizes synchronization techniques into the following structured hierarchy:

**Pillar 1: Synchronized Methods**
- Declared using the `synchronized` modifier.
- The lock is acquired on the **current object instance** (`this`) for instance methods.
- For `static synchronized` methods, the lock is on the **Class object** (`ClassName.class`).

**Pillar 2: Synchronized Blocks**
- Finer-grained locking — only wraps the **critical section** rather than the entire method.
- Lock object can be explicitly specified: `synchronized(obj) { ... }`.
- **Preferred** over synchronized methods for performance (less contention).

**Pillar 3: Explicit Locks (`java.util.concurrent.locks`)**
- `ReentrantLock`, `ReadWriteLock` from `java.util.concurrent` package.
- Provides advanced features: **fairness policy**, **tryLock()**, **interruptible lock acquisition**.

### 2.2 The Underlying Theory — Monitor Pattern

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Every Java object is associated with a **monitor** (concept introduced by Per Brinch Hansen and Tony Hoare). A monitor enforces:
> 1. **Mutual Exclusion** — Only one thread can be "active" inside the monitor at any time.
> 2. **Condition Synchronization** — Threads can `wait()` for a condition to become true.

### 2.3 Inter-Thread Communication: `wait()`, `notify()`, `notifyAll()`

These methods are defined in `java.lang.Object` and **must be called inside a `synchronized` context**, otherwise `IllegalMonitorStateException` is thrown.

| Method | Behavior |
|--------|----------|
| `wait()` | Releases the lock and puts the current thread in the **waiting state** |
| `notify()` | Wakes up **one** arbitrarily chosen thread waiting on the same object's monitor |
| `notifyAll()` | Wakes up **all** threads waiting on the same object's monitor |

### 2.4 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| # | Construct | Syntax / Formula | Lock Acquired On | When to Use |
|---|-----------|------------------|------------------|-------------|
| 1 | Synchronized Instance Method | `synchronized void method() { }` | `this` (current object) | Whole method needs protection |
| 2 | Synchronized Static Method | `static synchronized void method() { }` | `ClassName.class` | Class-level shared static variables |
| 3 | Synchronized Block on `this` | `synchronized(this) { ... }` | `this` | Equivalent to synchronized method |
| 4 | Synchronized Block on Object | `synchronized(lockObj) { ... }` | `lockObj` | Multiple locks / finer granularity |
| 5 | `ReentrantLock` | `lock.lock(); ... lock.unlock();` | Explicit `Lock` object | Need fairness / tryLock |
| 6 | `wait()` | `obj.wait(milliseconds)` | Releases `obj`'s lock | Producer-Consumer pattern |
| 7 | `notify()` | `obj.notify()` | Same as `wait()` | Wake single waiting thread |
| 8 | `notifyAll()` | `obj.notifyAll()` | Same as `wait()` | Safer than `notify()` — KTU recommended |

### 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

In real engineering systems, thread synchronization is foundational to:
- **Banking transaction systems** — ensuring atomic withdrawal/deposit.
- **Database connection pools** — synchronizing access to pool objects.
- **Embedded sensor networks** (IoT) — synchronizing sensor data read/writes.
- **Multithreaded web servers** (Tomcat, Jetty) — managing concurrent client requests.

