## SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Java Program Implementation & Analytical Walkthrough

### 3.1 Problem Statement

> Design a Java program where **multiple threads** attempt to **withdraw money** from a **single shared bank account**. Demonstrate that without synchronization, the balance becomes **corrupted (race condition)**. Then fix it using the `synchronized` keyword.

### 3.2 Step 1 — Defining the Shared Resource Class (Without Synchronization)

```java
// File: BankAccount.java
class BankAccount {
    int balance;

    BankAccount(int balance) {
        this.balance = balance;
    }

    // UNSYNCHRONIZED — Vulnerable to race condition
    void withdraw(int amount) {
        if (balance >= amount) {
            System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() 
                + " is about to withdraw " + amount);

            // Simulating time delay — amplifies race condition
            try { Thread.sleep(100); } 
            catch (InterruptedException e) { System.out.println(e); }

            balance = balance - amount;
            System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() 
                + " completed withdrawal. Remaining: " + balance);
        } else {
            System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() 
                + " insufficient funds. Balance: " + balance);
        }
    }
}
```

**Analytical Trace (Race Condition Exposed):**

Let initial `balance = 1000`. Two threads, **T1** and **T2**, both call `withdraw(800)`.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Time } t_0 &: \quad T_1 \text{ reads } balance = 1000, \text{ passes check} \\
\text{Time } t_1 &: \quad T_1 \text{ enters } \text{sleep}(100) \\
\text{Time } t_2 &: \quad T_2 \text{ reads } balance = 1000, \text{ passes check (BUG!)} \\
\text{Time } t_3 &: \quad T_1 \text{ wakes, sets } balance = 1000 - 800 = 200 \\
\text{Time } t_4 &: \quad T_2 \text{ wakes, sets } balance = 200 - 800 = -600 \;\;(\text{CORRUPTION})
\end{aligned}
$$

> [!WARNING]
> This negative balance is the **classic race condition symptom** that KTU examiners love to test in viva. Always explain that `balance >= amount` check and the actual subtraction are **not atomic** — they are two separate JVM operations.

### 3.3 Step 2 — Applying the `synchronized` Fix

```java
// File: BankAccountSync.java
class BankAccountSync {
    int balance;

    BankAccountSync(int balance) {
        this.balance = balance;
    }

    // SYNCHRONIZED — Thread-safe
    synchronized void withdraw(int amount) {
        if (balance >= amount) {
            System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() 
                + " is about to withdraw " + amount);
            try { Thread.sleep(100); } 
            catch (InterruptedException e) { System.out.println(e); }
            balance = balance - amount;
            System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() 
                + " completed withdrawal. Remaining: " + balance);
        } else {
            System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() 
                + " insufficient funds. Balance: " + balance);
        }
    }
}
```

**How the Lock Mechanism Works (Analytical Trace):**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Time } t_0 &: \quad T_1 \text{ enters } \texttt{withdraw}, \text{ acquires lock on } \texttt{this} \\
\text{Time } t_1 &: \quad T_2 \text{ calls } \texttt{withdraw}, \text{ lock is held} \Rightarrow T_2 \text{ BLOCKED} \\
\text{Time } t_2 &: \quad T_1 \text{ sleeps while holding lock} \\
\text{Time } t_3 &: \quad T_1 \text{ wakes, } balance = 200, \text{ exits method, RELEASES lock} \\
\text{Time } t_4 &: \quad T_2 \text{ acquires lock, re-reads } balance = 200, \text{ check fails} \\
\text{Time } t_5 &: \quad T_2 \text{ prints "insufficient funds" and exits safely}
\end{aligned}
$$

### 3.4 Step 3 — The Main Driver Class

```java
// File: SyncDemo.java
public class SyncDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BankAccountSync account = new BankAccountSync(1000);

        // Lambda expression — Runnable functional interface
        Runnable task = () -> account.withdraw(800);

        Thread t1 = new Thread(task, "Thread-A");
        Thread t2 = new Thread(task, "Thread-B");
        Thread t3 = new Thread(task, "Thread-C");

        t1.start();
        t2.start();
        t3.start();
    }
}
```

### 3.5 Step 4 — Expected Output (Synchronized Version)

```
Thread-A is about to withdraw 800
Thread-A completed withdrawal. Remaining: 200
Thread-B insufficient funds. Balance: 200
Thread-C insufficient funds. Balance: 200
```

### 3.6 Step 5 — Alternative: Synchronized Block Implementation

For **finer-grained locking** (only the critical subtraction is synchronized):

```java
void withdrawBlockSync(int amount) {
    if (balance >= amount) {
        synchronized(this) {
            System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() 
                + " is withdrawing " + amount);
            try { Thread.sleep(100); } 
            catch (InterruptedException e) { System.out.println(e); }
            balance -= amount;
            System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() 
                + " done. Remaining: " + balance);
        }
    }
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> KTU examiners often ask: *"Why prefer synchronized block over synchronized method?"* — Answer: The block acquires the lock for a **shorter duration**, allowing other non-critical operations (like logging) to run concurrently, thus improving throughput.

### 3.7 Step 6 — Producer-Consumer Using `wait()` and `notify()`

```java
class SharedBuffer {
    int data;
    boolean available = false;

    synchronized void produce(int value) {
        while (available) {
            try { wait(); } 
            catch (InterruptedException e) { System.out.println(e); }
        }
        data = value;
        System.out.println("Produced: " + data);
        available = true;
        notify();
    }

    synchronized int consume() {
        while (!available) {
            try { wait(); } 
            catch (InterruptedException e) { System.out.println(e); }
        }
        System.out.println("Consumed: " + data);
        available = false;
        notify();
        return data;
    }
}
```

**Analytical State Machine:**

$$
\text{State Transition: } (\text{available}=false) \xrightarrow{\text{produce}} (\text{available}=true) \xrightarrow{\text{consume}} (\text{available}=false)
$$

The `while` loop is **critical** (instead of `if`) to guard against **spurious wakeups** — another favorite KTU viva point.

