## SECTION 5: KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

#### **Q1. [KTU University Exam - May 2024]**
**Define thread synchronization. What is a race condition?**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

> **Thread synchronization** is the mechanism that controls the access of multiple threads to shared resources, ensuring that only one thread can execute the critical section at a time. It is implemented in Java using the `synchronized` keyword.
>
> A **race condition** occurs when two or more threads access shared data concurrently, and the final outcome depends on the unpredictable order of execution. For example, if two threads simultaneously withdraw money from a bank account, the balance may become inconsistent (negative balance) because the read-check-update sequence is not atomic. Synchronization prevents this by enforcing **mutual exclusion**.

---

#### **Q2. [KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]**
**Explain the role of `wait()`, `notify()`, and `notifyAll()` in inter-thread communication.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

> These three methods, defined in `java.lang.Object`, facilitate **inter-thread communication** within synchronized code:
> - **`wait()`**: The current thread releases the intrinsic lock and enters the waiting state until another thread invokes `notify()` or `notifyAll()` on the same object. Overloaded form `wait(long millis)` also supports timed waiting.
> - **`notify()`**: Wakes up **one** arbitrarily chosen thread that is waiting on the same object's monitor.
> - **`notifyAll()`**: Wakes up **all** threads waiting on the same object's monitor, after which they compete for the lock.
>
> These methods **must be called from within a synchronized context**, otherwise `IllegalMonitorStateException` is thrown.

