#### **Question B (14 Marks)**

**[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023 Model Paper, Module 2]**

**(a)** What is a **deadlock**? Explain with an example. List **two ways** to avoid deadlock in Java multithreaded programs. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a Java program using **`wait()` and `notifyAll()`** to implement the **Producer-Consumer problem** where the buffer size is **1**. The producer should produce a value only when the buffer is empty, and the consumer should consume only when the buffer is full. **(7 marks)**

---

**Model Solution:**

**(a) Deadlock (7 marks):**

A **deadlock** occurs when two or more threads are permanently blocked, each waiting for a lock that the other holds. It satisfies four **Coffman conditions** simultaneously:
1. **Mutual Exclusion** — Lock is non-shareable.
2. **Hold and Wait** — Thread holds one lock while waiting for another.
3. **No Preemption** — Locks cannot be forcibly taken.
4. **Circular Wait** — A cyclic dependency chain exists among threads.

**Example:**
```java
class A { synchronized void methodA(B b) { b.last(); } 
          synchronized void last() { System.out.println("A.last"); } }
class B { synchronized void methodB(A a) { a.last(); } 
          synchronized void last() { System.out.println("B.last"); } }
```
If Thread-1 calls `a.methodA(b)` while Thread-2 calls `b.methodB(a)`, and each acquires only one lock, both threads wait forever.

**Two ways to avoid deadlock:**
1. **Lock Ordering** — Always acquire locks in a **fixed global order** (e.g., always lock object A before B).
2. **Lock Timeout with `tryLock()`** — Use `ReentrantLock.tryLock(timeout, unit)` and release acquired locks if the second lock cannot be obtained.

**(b) Producer-Consumer Program (7 marks):**

```java
class Buffer {
    private int data;
    private boolean full = false;

    synchronized void produce(int value) throws InterruptedException {
        while (full) {
            wait();   // wait if buffer is full
        }
        data = value;
        System.out.println("Produced: " + data);
        full = true;
        notifyAll();  // wake up consumer
    }

    synchronized int consume() throws InterruptedException {
        while (!full) {
            wait();   // wait if buffer is empty
        }
        System.out.println("Consumed: " + data);
        full = false;
        notifyAll();  // wake up producer
        return data;
    }
}

class Producer extends Thread {
    Buffer buffer;
    Producer(Buffer b) { this.buffer = b; }
    public void run() {
        try {
            for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) buffer.produce(i);
        } catch (InterruptedException e) { System.out.println(e); }
    }
}

class Consumer extends Thread {
    Buffer buffer;
    Consumer(Buffer b) { this.buffer = b; }
    public void run() {
        try {
            for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) buffer.consume();
        } catch (InterruptedException e) { System.out.println(e); }
    }
}

public class ProducerConsumerDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Buffer buffer = new Buffer();
        Producer p = new Producer(buffer);
        Consumer c = new Consumer(buffer);
        p.start();
        c.start();
    }
}
```

**Sample Output:**
```
Produced: 1
Consumed: 1
Produced: 2
Consumed: 2
...
```

