# Section 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

A **Java Swing-based Simple Calculator** is a **Graphical User Interface (GUI)** desktop application developed using the **Java Foundation Classes (JFC)** — specifically the **Swing API** (`javax.swing` package) — that emulates the functional behavior of a hand-held electronic calculator. The application constructs a top-level container (`JFrame`), embeds an **AWT/Swing text component** (`JTextField`) for result display, and arranges digit and operator buttons (`JButton`) using layout managers (commonly `GridLayout` or `java.awt.GridBagLayout`). Mathematical operations are delegated through a **single `ActionListener` interface** implementation, and **divide-by-zero anomalies** are intercepted using Java's **Exception Handling mechanism** (`try-catch-finally` blocks with `ArithmeticException`).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Scheme Definition Snapshot:** The experiment evaluates the student's ability to (a) instantiate Swing containers, (b) register and handle ActionEvents, (c) parse and evaluate arithmetic expressions, and (d) implement robust **exception handling** for runtime anomalies — directly mapping to **Course Outcome CO1** (Apply object-oriented constructs) and **CO2** (Develop GUI-based applications).

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — Plain English Intuition

> [!NOTE]
> **Analogy: The Cafe Counter Calculator**
> Imagine a small cafe counter with a digital display screen on the wall and a row of buttons below it. When the cashier presses the digit buttons (0-9), the number appears on the display. When they press an operator (+, -, *, %), the system *remembers* the first number and the operator. Finally, when they press the equals button, the system grabs the second number from the display, performs the saved operation, and shows the answer. If the cashier accidentally tries to divide a bill of ₹500 by 0 people, the system doesn't crash or display garbage — instead, it politely shows a "Cannot Divide By Zero" message. **That is exactly what our Java Swing calculator does, but inside the JVM (Java Virtual Machine)!**

The mapping is:

| Cafe Counter Concept | Java Swing Equivalent |
|----------------------|----------------------|
| Wall-mounted display | `JTextField` |
| Physical buttons | `JButton` instances |
| Cashier's brain remembering state | Class-level `double` variables |
| Alarm for invalid operations | `try-catch (ArithmeticException)` |
| Counter layout | `JFrame` + `GridLayout` |

## 1.3 Physical / Design Constants & Standard Metrics

- **Recommended Window Size:** `400 × 500` pixels (width × height).
- **Font for Display:** `Arial`, **Bold**, size **24 px**.
- **Button Font:** `Arial`, **Plain**, size **18 px**.
- **Grid Layout Dimensions:** **4 rows × 4 columns** (16 cells for digits + operators + clear + equals).
- **Swing Threading Model:** All GUI component creation and event handling **must** occur on the **Event Dispatch Thread (EDT)** — typically wrapped inside `SwingUtilities.invokeLater(Runnable r)`.

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Common Mistake:** Creating Swing components directly inside `main()` without dispatching them to the EDT is a frequent deduction point. Examiners specifically look for `SwingUtilities.invokeLater()` in the model answer.

