# Section 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Theoretical Decomposition — The Five Architectural Layers

A Swing calculator is **not** a single monolithic program. It is a layered architecture with five clearly separable concerns. KTU examiners reward students who identify and explain these layers explicitly in viva-voce.

### Layer 1 — The Top-Level Window (Container Layer)
- Class used: `javax.swing.JFrame`
- Method chain: `setTitle()`, `setSize()`, `setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE)`, `setLayout()`, `setVisible(true)`.
- The `JFrame` is the **root container** — every other component must ultimately attach to it (directly or via intermediate panels).

### Layer 2 — The Display Component (Output Layer)
- Class used: `javax.swing.JTextField`
- Configuration: `setEditable(false)` to prevent the user from typing into the display; `setHorizontalAlignment(JTextField.RIGHT)` to mimic real calculators.
- The `JTextField` is a **passive view** — it never triggers events; it only *receives* state updates from the controller.

### Layer 3 — The Input Components (Event Source Layer)
- Class used: `javax.swing.JButton` — instantiated **16 times** (10 digits + 4 operators + 1 clear + 1 equals).
- Each button is a **potential event source**. When the user clicks, the JVM fires an `ActionEvent` object.

### Layer 4 — The Controller (Event Listener Layer)
- Interface implemented: `java.awt.event.ActionListener` (functional interface — supports lambda expressions since Java 8).
- Mandatory override: `public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)`.
- The controller maintains **state** in the form of class-level fields: `num1`, `operator`, `startNewNumber`.

### Layer 5 — The Computation Engine (Business Logic Layer)
- Performs the actual arithmetic using Java's `double` (or `BigDecimal` for precision) primitives.
- For modulo (`%`), Java uses the **remainder operator** defined as: `a % b = a - (a / b) * b` where `/` is integer or floating-point division.

## 2.2 The State Machine of a Simple Calculator

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Conceptual Model:** A calculator is a **Finite State Machine (FSM)** with the following five states:
> 1. **IDLE** — display shows "0", no operator pending.
> 2. **ENTERING_FIRST_OPERAND** — user pressing digits accumulates them into `num1`.
> 3. **OPERATOR_PRESSED** — user pressed +, -, *, or %; we await the second operand.
> 4. **ENTERING_SECOND_OPERAND** — digits accumulate into `num2`.
> 5. **SHOWING_RESULT** — equals was pressed; display shows the computed value; pressing a digit resets to IDLE.

## 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet (Markdown Table)

| **Concept** | **Formula / Syntax** | **Boundary / Note** |
|-------------|----------------------|---------------------|
| Division operator | `a / b` | Throws `ArithmeticException` if `b == 0` **only for integer division**; `double` division returns `Infinity` or `NaN`. |
| Modulo operator | `a % b` | For `b == 0`, Java returns `NaN` (for doubles) or throws `ArithmeticException` (for integers). |
| TextField readout | `display.setText(String.valueOf(result))` | Must use `String.valueOf()` to avoid compilation error (double → String conversion). |
| Event registration | `button.addActionListener(this)` | `this` works only when the enclosing class `implements ActionListener`. |
| EDT dispatch | `SwingUtilities.invokeLater(() -> { ... });` | Mandatory for thread-safety in Swing. |
| Layout: 4×4 Grid | `panel.setLayout(new GridLayout(4, 4, 5, 5));` | Last two args are horizontal & vertical gaps (pixels). |
| Frame close behavior | `frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE)` | Alternative constants: `DISPOSE_ON_CLOSE`, `HIDE_ON_CLOSE`, `DO_NOTHING_ON_CLOSE`. |
| Number parsing | `Double.parseDouble(display.getText())` | Throws `NumberFormatException` on empty/non-numeric strings. |
| Lambda for ActionListener | `(e) -> { ... }` | Valid since Java 8 — KTU accepts this; `actionPerformed` override is the traditional form. |
| Exception syntax | `try { ... } catch (ArithmeticException e) { ... }` | Use `e.getMessage()` for diagnostic output. |

