# Section 3: Step-by-Step Code Construction & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Complete, Commented, Board-Exam-Ready Java Program

The program below is the **canonical KTU 2024 model answer**. Every line is annotated for the student. Read it once, then re-implement it by hand.

```java
// ============================================================
// Program: Simple Calculator using Java Swing
// Course : PCEOL408 - Object Oriented Programming (Java) Lab
// Module : 2 - GUI Programming using AWT and Swing
// KTU 2024 Scheme
// ============================================================

import javax.swing.*;          // Swing components (JFrame, JButton, JTextField, etc.)
import java.awt.*;             // AWT layout managers (BorderLayout, GridLayout) and fonts
import java.awt.event.*;       // ActionListener and ActionEvent interfaces

public class SimpleCalculator extends JFrame implements ActionListener {

    // -------- LAYER 1: Top-level window + display components --------
    private JTextField display;        // The result display field
    private JPanel buttonPanel;        // Container that holds all buttons

    // -------- LAYER 4: Controller state variables --------
    private String operator = "";      // Stores the last pressed operator (+, -, *, %)
    private double num1 = 0;           // Stores the first operand
    private boolean startNewNumber = true; // Flag: true => next digit overwrites display

    // -------- Constructor: builds the GUI --------
    public SimpleCalculator() {

        // --- Configure the JFrame (the top-level window) ---
        setTitle("KTU Simple Calculator");
        setSize(400, 500);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setLayout(new BorderLayout(5, 5));   // BorderLayout with 5px gaps

        // --- Configure the display text field ---
        display = new JTextField("0");
        display.setEditable(false);          // User cannot type into display
        display.setFont(new Font("Arial", Font.BOLD, 24));
        display.setHorizontalAlignment(JTextField.RIGHT);
        add(display, BorderLayout.NORTH);    // Display goes to the top region

        // --- Configure the button panel (4x4 grid) ---
        buttonPanel = new JPanel();
        buttonPanel.setLayout(new GridLayout(4, 4, 5, 5));

        // Button labels in row-major order (left-to-right, top-to-bottom)
        String[] buttons = {
            "7", "8", "9", "/",
            "4", "5", "6", "*",
            "1", "2", "3", "-",
            "C", "0", "=", "+"
        };

        // Instantiate each button, register listener, add to panel
        for (String label : buttons) {
            JButton btn = new JButton(label);
            btn.setFont(new Font("Arial", Font.PLAIN, 18));
            btn.addActionListener(this);     // 'this' refers to SimpleCalculator
            buttonPanel.add(btn);
        }

        add(buttonPanel, BorderLayout.CENTER);  // Grid panel occupies center
        setVisible(true);                       // Show the window
    }

    // -------- Event Handler: invoked when ANY button is clicked --------
    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        String command = e.getActionCommand();  // Read label of clicked button

        // CASE 1: A digit was pressed (0-9)
        if (command.matches("[0-9]")) {
            if (startNewNumber) {
                display.setText(command);       // Replace the display content
                startNewNumber = false;
            } else {
                display.setText(display.getText() + command); // Append digit
            }
        }
        // CASE 2: The Clear button was pressed
        else if (command.equals("C")) {
            display.setText("0");
            num1 = 0;
            operator = "";
            startNewNumber = true;
        }
        // CASE 3: An operator button was pressed (+, -, *, /, %)
        else if (command.equals("+") || command.equals("-") ||
                 command.equals("*") || command.equals("/") || command.equals("%")) {

            // Step A: Store the current display value as the FIRST operand
            num1 = Double.parseDouble(display.getText());
            // Step B: Remember which operator was chosen
            operator = command;
            // Step C: Prepare to receive the second operand
            startNewNumber = true;
        }
        // CASE 4: The Equals button was pressed
        else if (command.equals("=")) {
            try {
                // Step A: Parse the second operand from the display
                double num2 = Double.parseDouble(display.getText());
                double result = 0;

                // Step B: Perform the operation based on stored operator
                switch (operator) {
                    case "+": result = num1 + num2; break;
                    case "-": result = num1 - num2; break;
                    case "*": result = num1 * num2; break;
                    case "/":
                        // ---- EXCEPTION HANDLING FOR DIVIDE BY ZERO ----
                        if (num2 == 0) {
                            throw new ArithmeticException("Cannot divide by zero!");
                        }
                        result = num1 / num2;
                        break;
                    case "%": result = num1 % num2; break;
                    default:
                        display.setText("Error: No operator");
                        return;
                }

                // Step C: Show the result
                display.setText(String.valueOf(result));
                startNewNumber = true;  // Next digit press starts fresh

            } catch (ArithmeticException ex) {
                // Gracefully catch the divide-by-zero exception
                display.setText("Error: " + ex.getMessage());
                startNewNumber = true;
            } catch (NumberFormatException ex) {
                // Catch any malformed number parsing errors
                display.setText("Error: Invalid Input");
                startNewNumber = true;
            }
        }
    }

    // -------- main method: Entry point, dispatches to EDT --------
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // ALWAYS create Swing GUIs on the Event Dispatch Thread
        SwingUtilities.invokeLater(() -> new SimpleCalculator());
    }
}
```

## 3.2 Line-by-Line Analytical Matrix

| **Line Block** | **What It Does** | **Why It Is Necessary** |
|----------------|------------------|--------------------------|
| `extends JFrame` | Inherits window behavior (title bar, minimize, close) | Avoids manual window decoration code. |
| `implements ActionListener` | Marks this class as a listener for button clicks | Required for `addActionListener(this)`. |
| `JTextField display = new JTextField("0")` | Creates a non-editable readout | Mimics physical calculator screens. |
| `new GridLayout(4, 4, 5, 5)` | Lays buttons in 4×4 grid with 5px gaps | Predictable button placement. |
| `for (String label : buttons) { ... }` | Loops through 16 labels, creates 16 buttons | DRY principle — avoids repetitive `new JButton(...)` calls. |
| `btn.addActionListener(this)` | Subscribes the calculator to button events | Without this, buttons do nothing. |
| `command.matches("[0-9]")` | Regex check for a single digit 0–9 | Distinguishes digit buttons from operator buttons. |
| `startNewNumber` flag | Prevents digit concatenation after operator press | State machine management. |
| `num1 = Double.parseDouble(...)` | Converts display text → numeric | Foundation for arithmetic. |
| `throw new ArithmeticException(...)` | Manually throws when `num2 == 0` | Java does **not** throw this for `double` division — we must. |
| `try { ... } catch (ArithmeticException e)` | Catches and displays divide-by-zero error | **Mandatory part of the experiment question.** |
| `SwingUtilities.invokeLater(...)` | Schedules GUI creation on EDT | Thread-safety — prevents race conditions. |

## 3.3 Step-by-Step Execution Trace (Analytical Walkthrough)

Let's trace the user sequence: **Press 7 → Press 8 → Press + → Press 3 → Press =**.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Step 1: Button "7" pressed} &\rightarrow \text{command = "7"} \rightarrow \text{display = "7"} \rightarrow \text{startNewNumber = false} \\[4pt]
\text{Step 2: Button "8" pressed} &\rightarrow \text{command = "8"} \rightarrow \text{display = "78"} \\[4pt]
\text{Step 3: Button "+" pressed} &\rightarrow \text{num1 = 78.0},\ \text{operator = "+"},\ \text{startNewNumber = true} \\[4pt]
\text{Step 4: Button "3" pressed} &\rightarrow \text{startNewNumber is true} \rightarrow \text{display = "3"} \rightarrow \text{startNewNumber = false} \\[4pt]
\text{Step 5: Button "=" pressed} &\rightarrow \text{num2 = 3.0} \\[4pt]
\text{Step 6: switch("+")} &\rightarrow \text{result = 78.0 + 3.0 = 81.0} \\[4pt]
\text{Step 7: display.setText("81.0")} &\rightarrow \text{User sees 81.0 on screen}
\end{aligned}
$$

### Edge-Case Trace: Division by Zero

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Press 9, /, 0, =} &\rightarrow \text{num1 = 9.0},\ \text{operator = "/"},\ \text{num2 = 0.0} \\[4pt]
\text{Switch case "/"} &\rightarrow \text{Check: } \text{num2} == 0 \rightarrow \text{true} \\[4pt]
\text{Throw ArithmeticException} &\rightarrow \text{Catch block executes} \\[4pt]
\text{display.setText("Error: Cannot divide by zero!")} &\rightarrow \text{Graceful failure, no crash}
\end{aligned}
$$

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Critical Java Nuance:** Java's `double` division `9.0 / 0.0` does **NOT** throw an exception — it returns `Infinity` (or `NaN` for `0.0 / 0.0`). Only `int`/`long` integer division throws `ArithmeticException`. This is why the program **manually checks** `if (num2 == 0)` and throws an exception explicitly. Examiners love asking this as a viva question!

