# Section 5: KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

> **[KTU University Exam - May 2024]**

### Question 1: What is the role of `JTextField` in a Swing calculator? Why is `setEditable(false)` used?

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
A `JTextField` (from `javax.swing` package) acts as the **display component** of the calculator, showing the current numeric value to the user. It is a single-line text input/output component.

The method `setEditable(false)` is invoked to **prevent the user from typing arbitrary characters directly into the display** using the keyboard. This mimics real-world calculators where input is exclusively through button presses, preserving the integrity of the state machine. Without this, the user could bypass the controller and inject malformed strings (e.g., `"abc"`) that would crash `Double.parseDouble()` with a `NumberFormatException`.

*(Mark distribution: 1 mark for JTextField role, 1 mark for package, 1 mark for setEditable justification.)*

---

> **[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]**

### Question 2: Differentiate between AWT and Swing. Which one is preferred for developing GUIs in Java and why?

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

| **Aspect** | **AWT (`java.awt`)** | **Swing (`javax.swing`)** |
|------------|----------------------|---------------------------|
| Package | `java.awt` (heavyweight) | `javax.swing` (lightweight) |
| Components | Platform-dependent (uses OS peers) | Platform-independent (pure Java) |
| Pluggable Look & Feel | Not supported | Fully supported |
| Component class prefix | `Button`, `TextField` | `JButton`, `JTextField` |

**Swing is preferred** because (a) it is **lightweight** and renders consistently across operating systems, (b) it supports the **Pluggable Look and Feel (PLAF)** architecture allowing UI customization, (c) it offers richer components like `JTable`, `JTree`, and `JTabbedPane` that AWT lacks, and (d) it follows the **MVC pattern** rigorously, separating data from presentation.

*(Mark distribution: 1 mark differentiation table, 1 mark Swing advantages, 1 mark MVC mention.)*

