## 5.2 Part B — Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each, with Internal Choice)

> **[KTU University Exam - Module 2 Internal Choice Pattern, 2024 Scheme]**

### Question A (14 Marks):

**(a)** Explain the Swing class hierarchy. Describe the role of top-level containers, intermediate containers, and atomic components with examples. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a complete Java program using Swing to design a simple calculator with buttons for digits 0-9, the four basic arithmetic operators (+, -, *, /), a clear button (C), an equals button (=), and a text field to display the result. Implement **exception handling** to gracefully display an error message when the user attempts to divide by zero. **(7 marks)**

---

#### Part (a) Model Answer (7 marks):

The **Swing class hierarchy** is rooted in `java.awt.Component` and branches into a rich tree of GUI classes.

**Level 1 — Root:** `java.awt.Component` — the abstract superclass of all AWT/Swing UI elements.

**Level 2 — Container:** `java.awt.Container` extends `Component` and can hold other components. This is the parent of all windows and panels.

**Level 3 — Top-Level Containers** (subclass of `Container`, directly interact with the OS window manager):
- `javax.swing.JFrame` — a window with title bar, minimize/maximize/close buttons.
- `javax.swing.JDialog` — a pop-up dialog window.
- `javax.swing.JApplet` — embedded in a browser (deprecated in modern Java).

**Level 4 — Intermediate Containers** (subclass of `JComponent`, hold other components but cannot stand alone):
- `javax.swing.JPanel` — a generic container, often used with layout managers.
- `javax.swing.JScrollPane` — provides scrollbars for scrollable content.
- `javax.swing.JTabbedPane` — tabbed interface.
- `javax.swing.JToolBar` — toolbars with buttons.

**Level 5 — Atomic Components** (leaf components, cannot contain other components):
- `javax.swing.JButton` — clickable button.
- `javax.swing.JTextField` — single-line text input.
- `javax.swing.JLabel` — non-editable text/image.
- `javax.swing.JCheckBox`, `JRadioButton`, `JSlider`, `JComboBox`.

**Why this hierarchy matters:** Top-level containers establish the *root* window; intermediate containers organize *layout*; atomic components provide *user interaction*. The MVC separation enforced by this tree is what makes Swing both powerful and maintainable.

*(Mark distribution: 1 mark hierarchy root, 2 marks top-level, 2 marks intermediate, 2 marks atomic.)*

