## 5.3 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Where KTU students LOSE marks on this experiment — and how to avoid it:**
>
> 1. **Missing `SwingUtilities.invokeLater()` in `main()` (–1 to 2 marks).** Examiners specifically scan for this. Always wrap GUI creation in `invokeLater`.
> 2. **Forgetting `setEditable(false)` on the `JTextField` (–1 mark).** This signals you don't understand the role of the display vs. input components.
> 3. **Using `int` division without zero-check (–2 marks).** If you declare `int a, b` and divide, Java throws an *unhandled* `ArithmeticException` that crashes the program. The question explicitly demands graceful handling.
> 4. **Not resetting state after equals (–1 mark).** After pressing `=`, if the user presses another digit, the display should overwrite, not concatenate. Use the `startNew` flag correctly.
> 5. **Forgetting to call `addActionListener(this)` on buttons (–2 marks).** Buttons without listeners are *dead* — the program compiles but does nothing. This is the #1 silent-failure mistake.
> 6. **Using `==` to compare `String` objects (–1 mark).** Always use `.equals()` for String comparison in Java.

