## 5.4 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!TIP]
> **Last-Minute Revision Checklist — pin this to your lab journal cover page:**

- **Swing** is a lightweight GUI toolkit in `javax.swing`; always use `J*` prefixed classes (`JFrame`, `JButton`, `JTextField`).
- **Top-level container** for any standalone Swing app is `JFrame`; its `setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE)` ensures the JVM terminates on close.
- **Layout Managers:** `BorderLayout` (NORTH/SOUTH/EAST/WEST/CENTER) for top-level division; `GridLayout(rows, cols, hgap, vgap)` for uniform grids.
- **`JTextField` is read-only by default behavior** — call `setEditable(false)` to enforce it; call `setHorizontalAlignment(RIGHT)` to mimic calculator readouts.
- **`JButton` requires `addActionListener(listener)`** to be functional. A button without a listener is a visual no-op.
- **`ActionListener` is a functional interface** with one method: `actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)`. Use `e.getActionCommand()` to retrieve the button's label.
- **State management** in a calculator requires at least three fields: a `double num1` for the first operand, a `String operator` for the pending operation, and a `boolean startNew` flag.
- **Divide by zero handling:** Java's `double` division does NOT throw — you MUST explicitly check `if (divisor == 0)` and throw `ArithmeticException` manually, then catch it in a `try-catch` block.
- **Modulo (`%`) follows the same zero-check rule** as division; modulo by zero is mathematically undefined.
- **EDT rule:** All Swing component creation must happen on the **Event Dispatch Thread** via `SwingUtilities.invokeLater(Runnable r)`. Violating this can cause race conditions and visual glitches.
- **Number parsing:** `Double.parseDouble(String)` throws `NumberFormatException` on empty/non-numeric input — always validate display content before parsing.
- **String comparison:** Use `.equals()`, never `==`, when comparing button labels.
- **Compile command:** `javac SimpleCalculator.java` → run with `java SimpleCalculator`.
- **Set classpath** if using external JARs; for core Swing/AWT, no classpath is needed (they are part of the JDK).
- **Common exam trick:** examiner may swap the modulo symbol `%` with Java's remainder semantics — clarify that `%` is the **remainder operator**, not a true mathematical modulo, when dealing with negative numbers.

